  <article class="surface">
    <p class="eyebrow">Workshop · 06</p>
    <h1>Innovation Days</h1>

    <p>
      A full day for the team to try something outside the roadmap — a new tool, a proof of concept,
      or taking apart something that has quietly grown stale. I facilitate the day, help scope it
      realistically, and coach through the technical work as it unfolds.
    </p>

    <h2>What the day looks like</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>
        A short kickoff to align on the question the team is trying to answer — not the solution,
        the question.
      </li>
      <li>
        Scoping down to something that fits in a day. Most innovation days die of over-ambition
        before lunch; this is where the coach earns their keep.
      </li>
      <li>Focused build time, with me pairing where useful and out of the way where not.</li>
      <li>
        A close-out — what we learned, what we'd do differently, and whether the idea deserves a
        second day or a quiet burial.
      </li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Format</h2>
    <p>
      One full day, in-house or remote. Best for small teams (3–7 people) working on a single
      thread; larger groups tend to fragment and lose the day.
    </p>

    <h2>What you leave with</h2>
    <p>
      Either a prototype worth showing to the rest of the org, or the honest answer that the idea
      wasn't as good as it sounded — both are useful, and both are cheaper today than they would
      have been in a sprint next month.
    </p>

